    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:5774e8cb-9d5a-4006-b201-8fb350101831",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 12-year-old boy who appears his stated age, neatly dressed but slightly tense in unfamiliar settings. During conversation he is polite and cooperative, though he frequently fidgets with his sleeves, taps his foot, and glances toward his parent for reassurance before answering questions. He reports feeling “worried about a lot of things” nearly every day, including school performance, making mistakes, family safety, and whether friends are upset with him. His sleep is often restless, and he wakes feeling tired despite spending enough time in bed. He occasionally complains of stomachaches and headaches, especially on school mornings or before tests.\n\nHe lives with his mother, father, and a younger sister in a suburban neighborhood. {patientName} is in middle school and generally earns good grades, but teachers have noticed that he asks for repeated reassurance and takes a long time to start assignments because he wants them to be perfect. He enjoys drawing, building model kits, and playing soccer, although recently he has been avoiding team activities when he worries he might embarrass himself or let others down. He has a few close friends and gets along well with family members, but he can become irritable and tearful when overwhelmed.\n\nAt home, {patientName} tends to overprepare for routine events and repeatedly checks whether homework is packed, doors are locked, or plans have changed. His parents describe him as thoughtful and responsible, but increasingly “on edge.” He does not use tobacco, alcohol, or drugs. His diet is somewhat selective but adequate, and he drinks caffeinated soda occasionally, which seems to worsen his jitteriness. He spends moderate time on video games and online videos, especially in the evening, which may contribute to difficulty winding down at night.\n\nSocially, {patientName} is caring and sensitive to others’ opinions. He worries excessively about disappointing teachers and parents, and he often interprets minor setbacks as signs that something bad will happen. Despite these symptoms, he remains engaged in school and family life, with supportive caregivers who are seeking evaluation because his worry, muscle tension, poor concentration, and somatic complaints have been interfering with daily functioning for several months."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:0831093c-f847-4800-b0f6-139518a02387",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has had a long-standing tendency toward worry and perfectionism, but symptoms have become more pronounced over the past 8 to 10 months, particularly since transitioning to a more demanding school environment. He has no history of psychosis, mania, self-harm, or substance use. There is no reported history of developmental regression or major behavioral disturbance. His pediatric growth and development have otherwise been normal, and immunizations are up to date.\n\nHe has no major chronic medical illnesses. Past medical issues include intermittent tension-type headaches and functional abdominal discomfort, both of which tend to worsen during stressful periods. He has never been hospitalized for psychiatric reasons and has not previously taken psychotropic medication. He had brief school-based counseling last year for stress related to test anxiety, with partial benefit.\n\nLifestyle factors include high academic self-expectations, sensitivity to criticism, occasional caffeine intake, and inconsistent sleep hygiene due to evening screen use. Family members report that {patientName} often seeks reassurance repeatedly and has difficulty tolerating uncertainty. There is no known history of abuse, and the home environment is stable and supportive. Differential considerations that have been screened for include thyroid disease, anemia, stimulant exposure, and depression; current presentation is most consistent with generalized anxiety disorder."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
